{"title_page": "Imperium (Current 93 album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = Imperium\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Current 93]]\n| cover        = Current 93 imperium cover.jpg\n| released     = {{start date|1987}}\n| recorded     = 1987\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = {{Flatlist|\n* [[Industrial music|Industrial]]\n* [[Avant-garde music|avant-garde]]\n* [[neofolk]]\n* [[Minimal music|minimal]]\n* [[Ambient music|ambient]]\n}}\n| length       = 52:48\n| label        = {{hlist|Maldoror|[[Durtro]]}}\n| producer     = [[David Tibet]]\n}}\n\n'''Imperium''' is a [[studio album]] released in 1987 by the [[England|English]] experimental group [[Current 93]]. It was made during a musical style shift between the earlier abrasive [[Industrial music|industrial]] sound of Current 93, and the more [[neofolk]] inspired approach that would characterize most of their subsequent output. It was originally released as an LP in 1987 on the [[Maldoror (record label)|Maldoror]] label, but in 1992 it was also released as a CD on [[David Tibet]]'s [[Durtro]] label. Since then it has been reissued several times as both LP and CD on [[Durtro]]. The latest issue is from 2006, and is only for sale in [[Russia]] and CIS countries.<ref>[http://brainwashed.com/common/htdocs/discog/mal777.php?site=c93 \"Imperium\" at Brainwashed.com]</ref>\n\n==Background and composition==\nTracks in the first half of ''Imperium'' notably make use of slowed down and looped samples from [[Alan Stivell]]'s ''[[Renaissance of the Celtic Harp|Renaissance de la Harpe Celtique]]''.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| total_length = 52:48\n| title1  = Imperium I\n| length1 = 6:07\n| title2  = Imperium II\n| length2 = 5:47\n| title3  = Imperium III\n| length3 = 7:02\n| title4  = Imperium IV\n| length4 = 3:15\n| title5  = Time Stands Still\n| length5 = 2:57\n| title6  = Be\n| length6 = 0:53\n| title7  = Locust\n| length7 = 9:47\n| title8  = Or\n| length8 = 9:22\n| title9  = Alone\n| length9 = 7:36\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[David Tibet]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Current 93}}\n\n[[Category:1987 albums]]\n[[Category:Current 93 albums]]\n[[Category:Experimental music albums by English artists]]\n[[Category:Ambient albums by English artists]]\n[[Category:Drone music albums by English artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = Imperium\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Current 93]]\n| cover        = Current 93 imperium cover.jpg\n| released     = {{start date|1987}}\n| recorded     = 1987\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = {{Flatlist|\n* [[Industrial music|Industrial]]\n* [[Avant-garde music|avant-garde]]\n* [[neofolk]]\n* [[Minimal music|minimal]]\n* [[Ambient music|ambient]]\n}}\n| length       = 52:48\n| label        = {{hlist|Maldoror|[[Durtro]]}}\n| producer     = [[David Tibet]]\n}}\n\n'''Imperium''' is a [[studio album]] released in 1987 by the [[England|English]] experimental group [[Current 93]]. It was made during a musical style shift between the earlier abrasive [[Industrial music|industrial]] sound of Current 93, and the more [[neofolk]] inspired approach that would characterize most of their subsequent output. It was originally released as an LP in 1987 on the [[Maldoror]] label, but in 1992 it was also released as a CD on [[David Tibet]]'s [[Durtro]] label. Since then it has been reissued several times as both LP and CD on [[Durtro]]. The latest issue is from 2006, and is only for sale in [[Russia]] and CIS countries.<ref>[http://brainwashed.com/common/htdocs/discog/mal777.php?site=c93 \"Imperium\" at Brainwashed.com]</ref>\n\n==Background and composition==\nTracks in the first half of ''Imperium'' notably make use of slowed down and looped samples from [[Alan Stivell]]'s ''[[Renaissance of the Celtic Harp|Renaissance de la Harpe Celtique]]''.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| total_length = 52:48\n| title1  = Imperium I\n| length1 = 6:07\n| title2  = 