Bif Taylor ||\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[One Piece: Pirates Carnival]]'' || Bellamy the Hyena || English dub\n|}\n\n===Theatre===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2000\u201301 || ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Live!]]'' || James || Baritone/Tenor\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'' || Fender, [[Link Larkin]] || Replacement roles<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadway.com/buzz/94983/andrew-rannells-to-star-as-hairsprays-next-link-larkin|title=Andrew Rannells to Star as Hairspray's Next Link Larkin|website=broadway.com|last=Joy|first=Cara|date=November 11, 2005|accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2006 || ''The 60's Project'' || Performer || Chester, CT (Regional): World Premiere\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Jersey Boys]]'' || [[Bob Gaudio]] || US Tour: 1st National Tour, replacement role<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jerseyboysblog.com/jbb-exclusive-interview-with-andrew-rannells/2385#.U3kcFa22JhF|title=JBB EXCLUSIVE: Interview With Andrew Rannells!|website=jerseyboysblog.com|first=Cathi|last=Aradi|date=March 3, 2008|accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Lysistrata Jones]]'' || Michelangelo \"Mick\" Jackson || Originated role<ref>{{cite news|last1=Liner|first1=Elaine|title=The Dallas Theater Center's World Premiere, Give It Up! Asks The Audience To Give Up More Than Two And A Half Hours To Its Redbull-buzzed Idiocy|url=http://www.dallasobserver.com/arts/the-dallas-theater-centers-world-premiere-give-it-up-asks-the-audience-to-give-up-more-than-two-and-a-half-hours-to-its-redbull-buzzed-idiocy-6405994|accessdate=December 30, 2017|work=Dallas Observer|date=January 28, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[The Book of Mormon (musical)|The Book of Mormon]]'' || Elder Kevin Price || Originated role\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Hedwig and the Angry Inch (musical)|Hedwig and the Angry Inch]]'' || Hedwig || Replacement\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Hamilton (musical)|Hamilton]]'' || [[George III of the United Kingdom|King George III]] || Temporary five-week replacement for [[Jonathan Groff]]\n(Oct 27, 2015 - Nov 29, 2015)\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Falsettos]]'' || Whizzer Brown || Broadway revival\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[The Boys in the Band (play)|The Boys in the Band]]''|| Larry<ref>{{cite news |first=Olivia |last=Clement |date=December 15, 2017 |title=''The Leftovers''' Charlie Carver Joins Matt Bomer, Andrew Rannells, and More for Broadway's ''The Boys in the Band'' |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/the-leftovers-charlie-carver-joins-matt-bomer-andrew-rannells-and-more-for-broadways-the-boys-in-the-band |website=Playbill |accessdate=March 21, 2018 }}</ref> || Broadway\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Award \n!Category\n!Work\n!Result\n! {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2011\n|[[Tony Award]]\n|[[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical|Best Performance by a Leading Actor in a Musical]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" |''[[The Book of Mormon (musical)|The Book of Mormon]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actor in a Musical|Outstanding Actor in a Musical]]\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|[[Grammy Award]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Musical Theater Album|Best Musical Theater Album]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2013\n|OFTA Award\n|Best Guest Actor in a Comedy Series\n|rowspan=2|''[[Girls (TV Series)|Girls]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|Gold Derby Awards\n|Best Comedy Guest Actor\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|[[Dorian Awards]]\n| colspan=\"2\" |Rising Star\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2014\n|Gold Derby Award\n|Best Comedy Guest Actor\n|rowspan=2|''Girls''\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|[[Critics' Choice Television Award]]\n|Best Guest Performer in a Comedy Series\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|2015\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Broadway.com Audience Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Favorite Replacement (Male)\n|''[[Hedwig and the Angry Inch (musical)|Hedwig and the Angry Inch]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Hamilton (musical)|Hamilton]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|{{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadway.com/buzz/184680/vote-now-hamilton-breaks-record-for-most-broadwaycom-audience-choice-award-nominations/|title=Vote Now! Hamilton Breaks Record for Most Broadway.com Audience Choice Award Nominations |website=Broadway.com |date=April 29, 2016}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2017\n|Favorite Featured Actor in a Musical\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''[[Falsettos]]''\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|[[Tony Award]]\n|[[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Musical|Best Performance by Featured Actor in a Musical]]\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[LGBT culture in New York City]]\n* [[List of self-identified LGBTQ New Yorkers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|710330}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n*[http://voicechasers.com/database/showactor.php?actorid=2354 Andrew Rannells at Voice Chasers]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rannells, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:American male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:Broadway theatre people]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male video game actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Gay actors]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Nebraska]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Marymount Manhattan College alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American actor and singer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Andrew Rannells\n| image        = Andrew Rannells 2015.jpg\n| caption      = Rannells at the PaleyFest 2015\n| birth_name   = Andrew Scott Rannells\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1978|8|23|}}\n| birth_place  = [[Omaha, Nebraska]], U.S.\n| residence    = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| education    = [[Creighton Preparatory School]]\n| alma_mater   = [[Marymount Manhattan College]]\n| occupation   = Actor, voice actor, singer\n| years_active = 1995&ndash;present\n| known_for    = ''[[The Book of Mormon (musical)|The Book of Mormon]]''<br/> ''[[Falsettos]]''<br/>''[[Pok\u00e9mon Live!]]''\n| television   = ''[[The New Normal (TV series)|The New Normal]]''<br/>''[[Girls (TV series)|Girls]]''<br/> ''[[Black Monday (TV series)|Black Monday]]''\n| awards       = [[Grammy Award for Best Musical Theater Album]]<br/>''[[The Book of Mormon: Original Broadway Cast Recording|The Book of Mormon]]''}}\n\n'''Andrew Scott Rannells''' (born August 23, 1978) is an American actor, voice actor, and singer.\n\nRannells was nominated for the [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Leading Actor in a Musical]] for his performance as Elder Price in the 2011 Broadway musical ''[[The Book of Mormon (musical)|The Book of Mormon]]''. He won the 2012 [[Grammy Award for Best Musical Theater Album]] as a featured soloist on the musical's [[The Book of Mormon: Original Broadway Cast Recording|original Broadway cast recording]]. He received his second [[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Musical|Tony nomination]] in 2017 for his performance as Whizzer in the 2016 Broadway revival of ''[[Falsettos]]''. Other Broadway credits include ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'', ''[[Hamilton (musical)|Hamilton]],'' [[Hedwig and the Angry Inch (musical)|''Hedwig and the Angry Inch'']], ''[[Jersey Boys]]'', and ''[[The Boys in the Band (play)|The Boys in the Band]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nRannells was born in [[Omaha, Nebraska]], to Charlotte and Ronald Rannells.<ref name=OWH-Mormon-2011/> He is the fourth of five siblings, with three sisters and an older brother.<ref name=OWH-Mormon-2011>{{cite news|last=Fischbach|first=Bob|title=He has drive \u2014 and now Broadway|url=http://www.omaha.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20110501/LIVING/705019893|accessdate=April 6, 2014|newspaper=[[Omaha World-Herald]]|date=May 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=GirlonGuy-AishaTaylor-2014/> His ancestry is Polish and Irish.<ref>https://mobile.twitter.com/AndrewRannells/status/81386126954344448</ref>\n\nRannells attended Our Lady of Lourdes grade school in Omaha, and then [[Creighton Preparatory School]],<ref name=OWH-Mormon-2011/> an all-boys Roman Catholic school in Omaha.<ref name=GirlonGuy-AishaTaylor-2014>{{cite web|last=Taylor|first=Aisha|title=girl on guy 126: andrew rannells|url=http://girlonguy.net/podcast/girl-on-guy-126-andrew-rannells|work=girl on guy|accessdate=April 6, 2014|format=audio podcast|date=February 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name=SiouxCityJournal-Mormon-2011>{{cite web|last=Miller|first=Bruce R.|url=http://www.siouxcityjournal.com/entertainment/arts-and-theatre/article_e22c1390-a24d-5e3b-bfb6-958a7fffa3be.html|title='Nebraska native finds stardom in 'Book of Mormon'|work=[[Sioux City Journal]]|year=2011|accessdate=December 23, 2011}}</ref> His family lived in the [[Hanscom Park]] neighborhood in Omaha.<ref name=OWH-Mormon-2011/>\n\nAs a child, he took classes at the Emmy Gifford Children's Theater and performed at the [[Omaha Community Playhouse]] and the Firehouse Dinner Theatre and the Dundee Dinner Theatre.<ref name=OWH-Mormon-2011/><ref name=OmahaReader-Normal-2012>{{cite news|last=Francke|first=Warren|title=Omaha's Andy Now in New Normal: Oompa-Loompa Before Mormon Missionary|url=http://www.thereader.com/index.php/comments/omahas_andy_now_in_new_normal/|accessdate=6 April 2014|newspaper=The Reader (Omaha)|date=September 9, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407081753/http://www.thereader.com/index.php/comments/omahas_andy_now_in_new_normal|archivedate=April 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nRannells was 11 when he acted in his first play. He did community theater with fellow Omahan and Creighton Prep alumnus [[Conor Oberst]].<ref name=GQ-Mormon-2011/> He did voice-over work and commercials, including a 1996 ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]'' spoof with [[Amy Adams]].<ref name=GirlonGuy-AishaTaylor-2014/>\n\nRannells moved to New York City in 1997 after high school, studying theater at [[Marymount Manhattan College]] for two years before he started auditioning full-time and began landing roles.<ref>{{cite news|last=Yi|first=David|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/book-morman-star-andrew-rannells-college-dropout-turned-actor-suited-tonys-article-1.128282|title='The Book of Mormon' star Andrew Rannells: college dropout turned actor gets suited up for the Tonys|work=[[NY Daily News]]|date=June 9, 2011|accessdate=December 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRannells played the character James in ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Live!]]'' from September 2000 to August 2001, which he is embarrassed about, joking in 2019 that he would have rather starred in a [[porn film]] or [[snuff film]] instead and that he only took the job for the pay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatermania.com/broadway/news/flashback-friday-andrew-rannells-pokemon-live_77775.html|title=Flashback Friday: When Andrew Rannells Helped Pok\u00e9mon Meet Broadway|last=Levitt|first=Hayley|date=July 15, 2016|website=[[TheaterMania]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Andrew Rannells On Touring With Pokemon {{!}} Employee of the Month|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qnw0BXKk8Ow|language=en|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n\nFor about three years, from 2001\u201304, he worked with [[4Kids Entertainment]], a New York City animation production company, where his Omaha voice-over work served him well. He also directed a small number of video games, \"Kirby\" and \"Sonic the Hedgehog.\"<ref name=OWH-Mormon-2011/>\n\nAs a [[Voice acting|voice actor]], Rannells appeared in several [[4Kids Entertainment|4Kids]] and [[DiC Entertainment|DiC]] television programs and video games, such as ''[[Yu-Gi-Oh!]]''.<ref name=\"GQ-Mormon-2011\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/entertainment/movies-and-tv/201106/andrew-ranells-the-book-of-mormon |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130629094423/http://www.gq.com/entertainment/movies-and-tv/201106/andrew-ranells-the-book-of-mormon |url-status=dead|archive-date=June 29, 2013|title=Q&A: The Book of Mormon's Andrew Rannells|last=Rapkin|first=Mickey|work=[[GQ]]|date=June 9, 2011|accessdate=April 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBefore winning his first Broadway role, Rannells had parts in a number of regional theater productions, including ''Hedwig and the Angry Inch'', ''Miss Saigon'', and ''Thoroughly Modern Millie''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrew Rannells Tapped to Play Bob Gaudio in Jersey Boys|url=http://www.broadway.com/buzz/98004/andrew-rannells-tapped-to-play-bob-gaudio-in-jersey-boys|work=Broadway Buzz|publisher=Broadway.com|accessdate=May 17, 2014|author=Broadway.com Staff|date=December 30, 2008}}</ref>\n\nFor his turn as Hedwig at the Zachary Scott Theater Center in [[Austin, Texas]], in 2002,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/arts/2002-02-08/84558|title=Hedwig and the Angry Inch|publisher=}}</ref> he won best actor in a musical at the B. Iden Payne Awards in September 2002, which honor outstanding achievements in Austin theater.<ref>{{cite web|last=Faires|first=Robert|title=Articulations|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/arts/2002-10-04/103993/|publisher=The Austin Chronicle|accessdate=May 17, 2014|date=October 4, 2002}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he won the role of [[Link Larkin]] in the Broadway production of ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]''.<ref name=USAToday-Tony-2011>{{cite news|last=Truitt|first=Brian|title=Rannells relishes first Tony nomination|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/theater/awards/tonys/2011-06-09-andrew-rannells-tonys_n.htm|work=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=6 April 2014|date=June 9, 2011}}</ref> This was his first Broadway show, what he considers his big break. Rannells followed this with some regional performances.<ref name=GirlonGuy-AishaTaylor-2014/>\n[[File:Andrew Rannells 2009.jpg|thumb|upright=.7|left|Rannells in 2009]]\nRannells played [[Bob Gaudio]] in the First National Tour of ''[[Jersey Boys]]''. His last performance with the tour was on December 6, 2008, in [[Toronto]]. In January 2009, he reprised the role of Gaudio in the musical's Broadway production.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nRannells originated the role of Elder Price in ''[[The Book of Mormon (musical)|The Book of Mormon]]'', a musical written by ''[[South Park]]'' creators [[Trey Parker]] and [[Matt Stone]] and ''[[Avenue Q]]'' composer [[Robert Lopez]]. For his performance, he was nominated for the [[Tony Award for Best Leading Actor in a Musical]]. He won the [[Grammy Award for Best Musical Theater Album]] for his performance in the musical's ''[[The Book of Mormon: Original Broadway Cast Recording|Original Broadway Cast Recording]]''. His last performance was June 10, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hetrick|first=Adam|title=\"Two By Two\": Josh Gad and Andrew Rannells Will Be Succeeded By Jared Gertner and Nic Rouleau in ''Book of Mormon''|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/166746-Two-By-Two-Josh-Gad-and-Andrew-Rannells-Will-Be-Succeeded-By-Jared-Gertner-and-Nic-Rouleau-in-Book-of-Mormon|work=[[Playbill]]|date=June 6, 2012|accessdate=October 26, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120829143403/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/166746-Two-By-Two-Josh-Gad-and-Andrew-Rannells-Will-Be-Succeeded-By-Jared-Gertner-and-Nic-Rouleau-in-Book-of-Mormon|archivedate=August 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\nRannells played a stripper in the 2012 film ''[[Bachelorette (film)|Bachelorette]]''<ref>{{cite news|last=Ganz|first=Andrew|title=Book of Mormon's Andrew Rannells Takes It Off in \"Bachelorette\" Film; Comedy Available on VOD Aug. 10|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/168965|work=[[Playbill]]|date=August 10, 2012|accessdate=April 14, 2013}}</ref> and played a lead character, Bryan Collins, in the 2012-13 television series ''[[The New Normal (TV series)|The New Normal]]''.<ref name=HollywoodReporter-NewNormal-2012>{{cite web|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/hangover-justin-bartha-ryan-murphy-nbc-pilot-glee-293895|title='The Hangover Star Joins NBC's Ryan Murphy Comedy|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=February 22, 2012|accessdate=February 28, 2011}}</ref><ref name=SiouxCityJournal-Normal-2012>{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Bruce|title=Andrew Rannells sends up boss in 'New Normal'|url=http://siouxcityjournal.com/entertainment/arts-and-theatre/andrew-rannells-sends-up-boss-in-new-normal/article_c9569f57-b3ee-5eae-9895-d3515e511365.html|accessdate=April 6, 2014|newspaper=[[Sioux City Journal]]|date=November 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\nRannells played the recurring role of Elijah on the [[HBO]] television series ''[[Girls (TV series)|Girls]].''<ref name=WWD-Faith-2011>{{cite web |last=Lynch| first=Matthew| url=http://www.wwd.com/menswear-news/lifestyle/andrew-rannells-keeping-the-faith-3594177|title=Andrew Rannells: Keeping the Faith|work=[[Women's Wear Daily]]|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=February 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nRannells temporarily replaced [[Jonathan Groff]] in the role of King George III in ''[[Hamilton (musical)|Hamilton]]'' on Broadway from October 27 to November 29, 2015, while Groff fulfilled pre-arranged filming commitments.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Tony Nominee Andrew Rannells Will Step In for Jonathan Groff in Hamilton on Broadway|url=http://www.broadway.com/buzz/182185/tony-nominee-andrew-rannells-will-step-in-for-jonathan-groff-in-hamilton-on-broadway|website=Broadway.com|accessdate=2015-11-29}}</ref>\n\nRannells played the role of \"Whizzer Brown\" in the Broadway revival of ''[[Falsettos]]'' directed by [[James Lapine]]. He was joined by [[Christian Borle]] and [[Stephanie J. Block]] who played Marvin and Trina, respectively.<ref>Paulson, Michael. [http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2016/03/31/falsettos-revival-casts-its-leads-christian-borle-andrew-rannells-and-stephanie-j-block/?smid=tw-share \"\u2018Falsettos\u2019 Revival Casts Its Leads: Christian Borle, Andrew Rannells and Stephanie J. Block\"] ''The New York Times'', March 31, 2016.</ref> The musical ran from October 27, 2016 (with previews beginning September 29), to January 8, 2017.<ref>Gans, Andrew. [http://www.playbill.com/article/marvins-back-with-whizzer-as-falsettos-revival-begins# \"Marvin\u2019s Back with Whizzer, as 'Falsettos' Revival Begins\"] Playbill, September 29, 2016</ref><ref>Hetrick, Adam. [http://www.playbill.com/article/13-shows-close-as-broadway-gears-up-for-a-packed-spring# \"13 Shows Close as Broadway Gears Up for a Packed Spring\"], Playbill.com, December 29, 2016.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRannells is [[coming out|openly gay]].<ref name=Vulture-Girls-NewNormal-2012>{{cite news|last=Siegel|first=Miranda|title=Andrew Rannells on His Girls Character, Slapping Marnie, and His New Ryan Murphy Show | url=http://www.vulture.com/2012/05/andrew-rannells-girls-the-new-normal-interview.html|work=Vulture-[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=May 29, 2012|accessdate=October 26, 2012}}</ref> Rannells has said he has known he is gay since high school.<ref name=GirlonGuy-AishaTaylor-2014/> He came out to his family when he was eighteen, and by then they had already figured it out.<ref name=Vulture-Girls-2013>{{cite web|last=Martin|first=Denise|title=Andrew Rannells: The Boy Scout With the Dirty Mouth|url=http://www.vulture.com/2013/01/andrew-rannells-the-boy-scout-with-a-dirty-mouth-girls-new-normal-interview.html|work=Vulture-[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|accessdate=April 6, 2014|date=January 29, 2013}}</ref> He also came out to his theater friends, but not at the all-boys Catholic school.<ref name=GirlonGuy-AishaTaylor-2014/> As of 2014, he lives in New York City after temporarily residing in Los Angeles to film ''[[The New Normal (TV series)|The New Normal]]''.<ref name=GirlonGuy-AishaTaylor-2014/> Since 2019, he has been in a relationship with actor [[Tuc Watkins]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.towleroad.com/2019/09/andrew-rannells-tuc-watkins/|title=Andrew Rannells and Tuc Watkins Make Their Relationship 'Instagram Official'|date=2019-09-22|website=Towleroad Gay News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Pok\u00e9mon: Destiny Deoxys]] || Gur\u016b <br>(voice) || English dub\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Sex and the City 2]]'' || Wedding Chorus ||\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Bachelorette (film)|Bachelorette]]'' || Manny ||\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[The Intern (2015 film)|The Intern]]'' || Cameron ||\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Why Him?]]'' || Blaine Pederman ||\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[A Simple Favor (film)|A Simple Favor]]'' || Darren ||\n|-\n| 2020 || ''[[The Stand-In (2020 film)|The Stand-In]]'' || ||\n|-\n| 2020 || ''[[The Boys in the Band (2020 film)|The Boys in the Band]]'' || Larry ||\n|-\n| 2020 || ''[[The Prom (film)|The Prom]]'' || Trent Oliver ||\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1995\u201397 || ''[[Street Sharks]]'' || Streex, Shrimp Louie (voices) ||\n|-\n| 1999 || ''[[Archie's Weird Mysteries]]'' || [[Archie Andrews]] (voice) ||\n|-\n| 2000\u20132006 || ''[[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]]'' || Morty, Harley, Additional characters (voices) || English dub\n|-\n| 2001\u20132005 || ''[[Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Monsters]]'' || Mako Tsunami, Noah Kaiba, Leon von Schroeder / Leon Wilson (voices) || English dub\n|-\n| 2001 || ''[[Cubix]]'' || Connor ||\n|-\n| 2001 || ''[[Shaman King]]'' || Len Tao (voice) || English dub\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Kinnikuman]] || Additional characters (voices) || English dub\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Knight Hunters Eternity]] || Toudou Hijiri || \n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Tokyo Mew Mew]]'' || Dren, Wesley J. Coolridge III 